V{{for|the American writer|Damon Young (writer)}}\u000a{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\u000a{{Infobox philosopher \u000a|name = Damon Young\u000a|image = Damon_Young_in_2007.jpg \u000a|image_caption =\u000a|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1975}}\u000a|birth_place = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\u000a|school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy]] |\u000a|region = Western philosophy \u000a|era = [[Contemporary philosophy]]\u000a|color = #B0C4DE \u000a|main_interests = [[Aesthetics]], [[Eastern philosophy|Asian philosophy]], [[Rights]], [[Democracy]], [[Spirituality]], [[Environmental philosophy]], [[Martial arts]]\u000a|notable_ideas = Philosophy of distraction\u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Damon Young''' (born 1975 in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]) is an [[Australia]]n philosopher, writer and commentator, and author of the books ''Distraction'', ''Philosophy in the Garden'' and ''How to Think About Exercise''.<ref>[http://www.damonyoung.com.au Damon Young's website]</ref>  He is an Honorary Fellow in [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Melbourne]].<ref>[http://www.findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/researcher/person100033.html Damon Young's staff page at the University of Melbourne]</ref>\u000a\u000a==Work==\u000aIn 2013 Young won the Australasian Association of Philosophy's [http://www.aap.org.au/AAPmediaprize media prize] for his public writing and broadcasting.\u000a\u000aYoung is the author of ''Distraction'', an eclectic popular history of Western philosophy, focusing on themes such as attention to life and distraction from it, work, freedom and necessity.<ref>Boris Kelly, "Distraction" (Review), Overland, February 23, 2010, [http://overland.org.au/blogs/not-assigned/2010/02/distraction/ Overland.org]</ref><ref>Brad Frazier, "Review - Distraction", Metapsychology Online Reviews, Feb 16, 2010(Volume 14, Issue 7), [http://metapsychology.mentalhelp.net/poc/view_doc.php?type=book&id=5395&cn=394 Metapsychology.mentalhelp.net]</ref><ref>"Damon Young", Readings, [http://www.readings.com.au/interview/damon-young Readings.com.au]</ref>  The Australian called it lacking in precision, saying its "central proposition -- that new information technologies distract us from our common existential challenge -- is never thoroughly probed"<ref>Luke Slattery, "On paying attention" (Review of Distraction: A Philosopher's Guide to Being Free By Damon Young), The Australian, September 06, 2008, [http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/on-paying-attention/story-e6frg8no-1111117371752 The Australian.com]</ref> while London's ''Financial Times'' called it "lucid and optimistic".<ref>Mark Vernon, "Distraction" (Review), Financial Times, September 8, 2008, [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/cfd91158-7ad9-11dd-adbe-000077b07658.html FT.com]</ref>\u000a\u000a''Philosophy in the Garden'', published in Australia in December 2012, was described by ''The Australian'' as "fluent and stylish and never marred by cliches or cliched thinking".<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/ground-prepared-for-a-meandering-discourse/story-fn9n8gph-1226547206552 Theaustralian.com]</ref> It was published in the UK in April 2014 by Rider, an imprint of Random House, under the title ''Voltaire's Vine and Other Philosophies: How Gardens Inspired Great Writers''.<ref>[http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/editions/9781846044175 Random House] Retrieved 30 December 2014.</ref>\u000a\u000aYoung's columns, reviews and features have been published in ''The Age'', ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', ''The Australian'', \u000a''Herald-Sun'', BBC and ABC.<ref>[http://damon-young.blogspot.com.au/p/journalism.html Damon Young]</ref>  He has written poetry and fiction for ''Overland'' and ''Meanjin'' magazines.\u000a\u000aYoung regularly comments on radio, and has appeared on Channel 7 'Sunrise' and ABC TV. He was a regular panellist on ABC Radio National's 'Life Matters', a monthly guest on "Mornings" with Alan Brough on ABC 774, and was 'philosopher-in-residence' on "Afternoons" with James Valentine on ABC Sydney 702, and "sports philosopher" with Francis Leach on SEN 1116.<ref>[http://damon-young.blogspot.com.au/p/radiotelevision.html Damon Young]</ref>\u000a\u000a==Selected works==\u000a\u000aA full list of Young's published works and media appearances can be found at his website.<ref>[http://www.damonyoung.com.au/pubs.html Damon Young publications]</ref>\u000a\u000a===Books===\u000a* [http://www.randomhouse.com.au/books/damon-young/philosophy-in-the-garden-9780522857139.aspx ''Philosophy in the Garden'']. [[Melbourne University Publishing]], 2012 (Australian edition). ISBN 978-0-52285-713-9.\u000a* [http://catalogue.mup.com.au/978-0-522-85374-2.html ''Distraction'']. [[Melbourne University Publishing]], 2008 (Australian edition). ISBN 978-0-522-85374-2; [[Acumen Publishing]], 2010 (UK/US edition). ISBN 978-1-84465-254-9.\u000a* ''[http://www.opencourtbooks.com/books_n/martial_arts.htm Martial Arts and Philosophy]'', edited with Graham Priest, Open Court Publishing, 2010.  ISBN 978-0-8126-9684-4.\u000a* ''[http://www.theschooloflife.com/shop/howtothinkaboutexercise/ How To Think About Exercise]'', [[Macmillan Publishers]], 2014. ISBN 978-0-2307-6776-8.\u000a* ''[https://www.mup.com.au/items/164630 The Art of Reading]''. [[Melbourne University Publishing]], 2016. ISBN 978-0-522-867602\u000a\u000a===Essays and opinion===\u000a* 'Familiarity breeds content for grand old gallery's loyal patrons', ''The Age'' (21/4/11), p.&nbsp;13.\u000a* 'Super-rich exceptions are closer to being the rule', ''Sydney Morning Herald'', News Review (2/4/11), p.&nbsp;16.\u000a* 'Research the name of the game', ''The Australian'', Higher Education (2/3/11), p.&nbsp;5.\u000a* 'Legalizing mixed martial arts in New York', New York ''Daily News'' (16/1/11), p.&nbsp;13.\u000a* 'Turn video games into more than child's play', ''Sydney Morning Herald'' (14/1/11), p.&nbsp;9\u000a* 'The crisis and the cure', ''Sydney Morning Herald'', News Review (1/1/11), p.&nbsp;13.\u000a* 'You don't need Jesus to enjoy Christmas', ''Sydney Morning Herald'' (20/12/10), p.&nbsp;7.\u000a\u000a===Poetry===\u000a* 'The Idea of a Great Gallery', ''Overland'' 179 (2005): 41.\u000a*'Howard Watches the Oscars and Weeps With Joy', ''Overland'' 174 (2004): 124.\u000a\u000a===Fiction===\u000a* 'The Lesson', ''Meanjin'' 67 4 (2008), pp.&nbsp;128\u201335.\u000a\u000a===Recent academic essays===\u000a*'Bowing to Your Enemies: Courtesy, Budo and Japan', ''Philosophy East and West'' 59 2 (2009): 188-215.\u000a*'The Fine Arts of Distinction: Bourdieu on Society and Art', ''The Australian and New Zealand Journal of Art'' 7 2 (2006).\u000a* 'Being Grateful for Being: Being, Reverence and Finitude', ''Sophia'' 44 2 (2005): 31-53.\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a*{{official website|http://www.damonyoung.com.au}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Damon}}\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Australian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Continental philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\u000a[[Category:1975 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:University of Melbourne faculty]]\u000a[[Category:People from Melbourne]]
